      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Better Nursing Home Care''  (editorial, Sept. 25):</p>
        <p>Alice Gavin is 105. She lives at the  Washington Home, in the District of  Columbia. She has remained independent. She still bathes, dresses and feeds herself, as you mention.</p>
        <p>When President Clinton appeared,  she stood up. You write, ''It was, she  thought, the respectful thing to do.''  She showed respect for the presidency. Of course, at her age, remaining  seated would have also been appropriate.</p>
        <p>We can learn a lesson in civility  from this woman, well and alive, born in the 19th century. Long and healthy life, Miss Gavin.</p>
        <p>ELIE FEUERWERKER  Highland Park, N.J., Sept. 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
